+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01HS3n2ACs9BzKsytfj8kMf2","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The CRUD tests use `createApp()` (no seeding) and insert notes directly via SQL — bypassing the FTS sync. So when the PUT/DELETE routes try to do FTS delete with content from the `existing` note, the FTS index doesn't have that entry, causing SQLITE_CORRUPT_VTAB.\n\nThe fix: I need to handle the case where a note exists in the `notes` table but not in the FTS index. The safest approach is to use the `DELETE FROM notes_fts WHERE rowid = ?` approach instead of the content-based delete command, or better yet, use `content_sync` triggers. Actually, the cleanest fix with `content=` tables is to use `INSERT INTO notes_fts(notes_fts) VALUES('rebuild')` — but that's expensive. \n\nA better approach: Instead of using `content='notes'` (external content), I'll use a regular FTS5 table and manage the content ourselves. Or, I can wrap the FTS delete in a try-catch when content might not exist.\n\nActually, the real issue is that when notes are inserted via raw SQL in the CRUD tests, the FTS index doesn't get updated. The solution is to make the FTS operations resilient. Let me use `INSERT OR IGNORE` patterns and catch errors on the delete side. But the better approach is to just use triggers:"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":454,"cache_read_input_tokens":41623,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":454},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b28e8cb3-9916-47ab-bb4d-5c7d530afdbc","uuid":"47a652b3-90bc-4a3e-9379-18b209cb89e4"}
